class Solution {
    public int minimumOneBitOperations(int n) {
        int count = 0;
        while (n != 0) {
            n &= n - 1;
            count++;
        }
        return count;
    }
}
```

efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(log(n))
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW

Explanation:

The problem requires finding the minimum number of operations to set the rightmost bit of the number to 0. We can achieve this by repeatedly clearing the least significant bit using the bitwise AND operation with n - 1. The count of operations needed is incremented after each operation. The time complexity is O(log(n)) because we perform the operation until the number becomes 0, which is log base 2 of n. The space complexity is O(1) because we only use a single integer variable for counting operations. The energy implications are low because the algorithm only performs bitwise operations and does not involve any resource-intensive operations.

